    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-12-19T20:43:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-12-19T20:43:00-05:00" n="108"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                <head>108. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission to the United
                        Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d108fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> 8–3. Limited
                        Official Use.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1972-12-20T01:43:00+00:00">December 20, 1972,
                        0143Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5635. Subj: <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> Waldheim on 27th <gloss
                        target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In conversation with <gloss target="#t_AMB1">Amb</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">Bush</persName> Dec 10, <gloss target="#t_SYG1"
                            >SYG</gloss> Waldheim took somewhat philosophical view of 27th <gloss
                            target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>. He lamented that press in US, Europe and
                        virtually everywhere else was taking very negative <pb facs="0253" n="216"
                            xml:id="pg_216"/> view of accomplishments of 27th <gloss target="#t_GA1"
                            >GA</gloss>, calling it dull. Waldheim thought this was unfair. Dullness
                        of session was in large part a function of détente which had reduced
                        incidence of verbal fireworks.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Waldheim said he was of course disappointed that his terrorism initiative
                        had not borne more fruit. However, it was not fault of <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> organization that this and other “failures”
                        had occurred. If world community had attempted to deal with terrorism or
                        other unresolved problems outside context of <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                            >UN</gloss>, same cast of characters would have been involved.
                        Identifying Algeria, Libya, Syria and Iraq as particularly difficult to deal
                        with on terrorism (he mentioned consulting them before announcing his
                        terrorism initiative), he saw no reason to suppose that they would have been
                        easier to deal with outside <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGHW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Bush</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
